metadata.name: Breeding Grounds #55
metadata.description:
Social Networks.
Molecular Clouds.
Neuronal Circuitries.
Quantum Mechanical Structures.

Blurring Boundaries.
Infinite Self-Similarities.

Total.
Mess.

Perfect.
Order.

/////
Each element (besides the painting ground textures) is based on the underlying subdivided grid which is sometimes exposed like some kind of preliminary drawing.

Note on the split:
After seeing some of the outputs, Sermin had a dream about “Breeding Grounds” and I decided to incorporate events and feelings from her dream into the project. That's how the names of the color palettes came about. Thank you for naming them, Sermin!

Press 's' to save a .png with the current resolution (2000x3000).
If you want a file with higher resolution and/or without the “Painting Ground Textures” for printing please contact me via Twitter or Discord. 

/////
Created with p5.js

Twitter: @serminmin / @pxlshrd

metadata.name: CA Panico #100
metadata.description:
Third chapter of the trilogy dedicated to Stephen Wolfram's cellular automata.
 
Compared to CA Vista and CA Monti, CA Panico aims to further abstract the concept of landscape using CA rules in a more massive way.

The great variety of CA rules that controls the coloring and textures, noise influence, division into quadrants, chance of having glitches and outages all combined with 25 palettes and 5 different formats means that the outputs will be very varied and peculiar.

Press 'S' to download, you can zoom downloaded output to enjoy all the details.

metadata.name: iterations #400
metadata.description:
Multiple drawing methods create a broad range of stippled output. Inverted drawing (black on white, rather than white on black) is a 5% likelihood, and rainbo mode (all colors rather than one color) is a 1% likelihood. Health and happiness to you during this holiday season!

Created in p5.js

metadata.name: Gen DOS Punk #6
metadata.description:
Gen DOS Punks - A Generative Tribute to DOS Punks!

Each Punk is a unique 1/1.

222 fxrand() functions in total to ensure almost no duplicates whatsoever!

Features weren't included due to a technical limitation. However if you want to see those, you can check the console logs - they're all there!

You can also triple-tap on a phone or click S on your keyboard to perform a "right-click save as".

-----

Find me on Twitter @uoisnlli

And find the 'DOS Punks' creator on Twitter @maxcapacity

#DOSLIFE

Not affiliated with DOS Punks or CryptoPunks/Larva Labs

metadata.name: Wiggle #291
metadata.description:
Wiggle is a long-form generative collection of 1024 editions by Geoff Stearns that explores repetition using simple sine waves. There are 15 possible color palettes and the wave amplitude, complexity, and size are all variable.

The color palettes used in Wiggle are the same palettes used in Geoff's previous work, Hash Three Points (https://h3p.deconcept.com) and the projects share the same number of editions to invite collectors to find complimentary sets or pairs across the two projects.

https://twitter.com/tensafefrogs/status/1469491338714492929

metadata.name: Jellyfish #5
metadata.description:
Cognomen fxhash mint #3.

Each token features a jellyfish with a unique scrolling shader pattern and color scheme. The jellyfish are pixelated and dithered, and their pixel size, dithering pattern and color depth varies. The number of tentacles and their size is randomized.

There is a ~2% chance to mint a black and white jellyfish.

Created with Three.js by Mr. Doob.

metadata.name: Swimbot #232
metadata.description:
Swimbots are colorful wiggly creatures that evolved out of my artificial life experiments beginning in the mid 1990's. Now, as the result of a creative collaboration with Canton Becker, we're offering a limited number of artfully-mutated swimbots and releasing them into the wild, as NFTs.

Each NFT is a portrait of a unique swimbot flaunting its characteristic shape, wiggle, and coloration against a stylized background. Some backgrounds are quite rare.

Swimbots NFTs are more interesting when they interact! When placed into a common "gene pool", they mate, compete for food, and evolve... essentially forever. To that end, every NFT will also be spawned in a pool on the swimbots website. NFT holders can use this site to run simulations and competitions to see how good their swimbots are at propagating their genes into the future. Will your swimbot sink or swim?

https://www.swimbots.com/nft

metadata.name: outside.views #93
metadata.description: Generative art by Mark Knol (@mknol)

metadata.name: En Route #43
metadata.description: 'En Route' focuses on shadow work, delving deeply into the emotions, dreams, hopes, and fears that we often conceal within ourselves. Each piece is a visual representation of what lies within the depths of our unconscious minds and uses the power of circles and sacred geometry to symbolize totality, wholeness, and original perfection. By exploring the juxtaposition of depth and flatness, abstraction and figuration, shadow and brightness, this collection encourages us to confront and overcome the parts of ourselves that we may not want to face, but ultimately need to for our growth and healing.

metadata.name: Smash #64
metadata.description:
One way of understanding how something works is smashing it to pieces.

This generative art project is inspired by particle collision diagrams:
The results of subatomic clashes inside a particle accelerator.

All we get to see is a representation of trails, left behind by smashing the minuscule building blocks of reality at near the speed of light.

Press "S" to download 2k image.
Open live, type "&dpr=8" at the end of the URL, then press "S" to download 8k image.

metadata.name: barcodes #42
metadata.description:
The title of my collection is “barcodes”, as unique visual identifiers for their respective generative token. 

Barcodes initially displayed data by varying width, spacing, and size of the lines. Today, we can additionally separate barcodes by color and hidden layers.

In our realm of little dots and noise, we can distinguish data (token holder, contract address, purchase history) using these features, but we can add one more:

The time it takes for the “pitch to drop”. The pace of the barcode’s formation.

metadata.name: Celestial Objects #61
metadata.description:
Celestial Objects is a generative collection imagining planets and stars in the space, with light and shadows being key themes. 

The artwork is primarily rendered using hundreds of thousands of points (more than a million in some cases) to create different aspects of the output including the sky textures, shooting stars and shadows on the planets. 

Celestial Objects is coded in p5.js, and please note that it takes 5-15 seconds for each output to render.

Controls (in live view): 
Press [2] to render 2000x2000px image
Press [4] to render 4000x4000px image
Press [s] to save the current view (default window size or 2000px or 4000px image)

metadata.name: Cloverfield #120
metadata.description:
"Nature is the source of all true knowledge".

Have you ever taken the time to look, deeply look, at all the details in a humble patch of grass ?

In this tiny microcosm, a constant, fierce battle is going on, day after day, plants reaching out for sun, down for access to soil, fighting for survival. Smaller grasses form groups, alliances making it harder for taller ones to take over. Dead leaves remind us that some of them lost the fight, fallen warriors who, soon enough, will be forgotten too. Growth, decay, life, death, the endless cycle, right in front of our eyes.

It is fascinating, and, for me at least, an endless source of inspiration.

It is my hope that, through this project, you will take the time to take a closer look at nature, and that, as the pale blue dot we call home keeps getting drier and drier, remember that even humble patches of grass should not be taken for granted.


Key commands:
's' - save as png
'b' - make the background transparent (for printing)
'1', '2, '4' - set the pixel density, for resolutions up to 8000x8000

This updated version of the project should render on mobile devices, albeit with slightly reduced quality. 
If you want to save the image for printing, I recommend you do so on desktop.

metadata.name: Frozen Roses #17
metadata.description:
Each Frozen Rose is a unique, looping, generative animation.

Frozen Roses uses an underlying pattern of voronoi cells generated from a rotating pattern of points. The differences in these initial patterns of points result in a wide variety of unique shapes and structures. The voronoi pattern is then fed into a series of shaders designed with a user-guided evolutionary process to produce the final animations.
